'''Ōtomo Shrine''' (大伴神社) is a shrine located in {{ill|Saku, Nagano|ja|佐久市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Nagano Prefecture. The shrine is listed as a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|qq=draft|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
== Overview == According to the shrine's tradition, it was established in the 40th year of Emperor Keikō’s reign when {{ill|Ōtomo Takehi|ja|大伴武日|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (now worshiped as {{ill|Amenokushi-no-Mikoto|ja|天忍日命|1=Ama-no-Oshihi|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) descended to the area on horseback and enshrined himself there<ref name="#1">式内社研究会『式内社調査報告書 第十三・十四巻』（皇学館大学出版部）</ref>.
Another legend tells of {{ill|Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto|ja|月読命|qq=draft|qq=draft}} riding a dragon horse across the great ocean, surveying the rivers and valleys, ascending the Chikuma River, and enshrining himself at this location<ref>北條勝貴「松尾大社における市杵嶋姫命の鎮座について」『国立歴史民俗博物館研究報告 第72集』（1997th year 3月）</ref>.
During the {{ill|Taihō era|ja|大宝|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (701–704), imperial pastures (官牧) were established across the provinces. A plateau, 700 to 800 meters high, bordered by the Chikuma and Kakuma Rivers, was designated as a royal pasture directly managed by the court, becoming known as "Mochizuki Pasture" (望月牧). The local landholders, identified as descendants of the {{ill|Ōtomo clan|ja|大伴氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, were appointed as caretakers of the pastures. The Mochizuki clan, descended from the Ōtomo, also managed nearby Nagakura and Shiono Pastures.
The fame of Mochizuki's horses extended to the capital, inspiring a poem by {{ill|Ki no Tsurayuki|ja|紀貫之|qq=draft|qq=draft}}: *"At the pure waters of Ōsaka Barrier, I see shadows—surely Mochizuki's steed is being led away."*<ref name="#1"/>.
